ћ’Щ@cd665799d408c09cc9d0e069396c429ccd015f9ff5aebdeeb85a9a5bc4c80bd9ЪЯTitle: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: Nushell 0.77
Content:




Nushell, or Nu for short, is a new shell that takes a modern, structured approach to your command line. It works seamlessly with the data from your filesystem, operating system, and a growing number of file formats to make it easy to build powerful command line pipelines.
Today, we're releasing version 0.77 of Nu. This release adds reworked aliases, more consistent timestamp handling, reworked XML support, and more.
’Щ@ece71274d9e57669eb45a1be6d8008ab8a65a54419047bc67c49ffe971aa1ffbЪ4Title: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: Where to get it
Content:
Nu 0.77 is available as 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.77.0] pre-built binaries
 or from 
[link: https://crates.io/crates/nu] crates.io
. If you have Rust installed you can install it using 
``cargo install nu``
.
NOTE: The optional dataframe functionality is available by 
``cargo install nu --features=dataframe``
.
As part of this release, we also publish a set of optional plugins you can install and use with Nu. To install, use 
``cargo install nu_plugin_<plugin name>``
.
’Щ@25d2b6303020b668ec611980458de26bc7817fab882df17c4fe5ed649bf2eca2ЪЦTitle: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: )
Content:
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8123] Aliases have been a constant source of panics and growing code complexity as a result of trying to patch the panics. In this release, we re-implement aliases from scratch. Instead of replacing spans of expressions, aliases are implemented as another type of command, quite like 
``extern``
 is used to implement known externals. Alias is a command that wraps another command call. As a result, in some cases, aliases do not behave exactly the same as before. Here are the key facts:
Alias can only alias another command call. For example, 
``alias la = ls -a``
 works, but the following does not:
``alias foo = "foo"``
``"foo"``
 is not a command call, use 
``alias foo = echo "foo"``
 instead
``alias lsn = (ls | sort-by type name -i)``
subexpression is not a command call, use a custom command instead
Alias cannot alias command named the same as the alias. E.g., 
``alias ls = ls -a``
 is not possible currently, and gives an unhelpful error message. We plan to fix this as soon as possible and in the future we aim for this to work.
Some parser keywords are not allowed to be aliased. Currently, 
``overlay``
 commands can be aliased but the other parser keywords can not. We can add support for aliasing more parser keywords in the future.
If some of the above is too limiting for you, the old aliases are still unchanged and available as 
``old-alias``
. Just change 
``alias``
 to 
``old-alias``
 and it should work the same as before. If there are no more problems with the new alias implementation, and we manage to iron out the recursive alias issue, we will remove 
``old-alias``
 in the next release, otherwise, we'll keep it around longer.
’Щ@5560e90ddd52e81d417a9cecc9b77736dc2f90762312dbca55947c96a15f12ebЪTitle: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: )
Content:
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8337] Simplified conversion between Nushell 
``date``
 type and unix timestamps (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8244] #8244
).
Nushell now standardizes on representing a Unix timestamp as a number of 
nanoseconds
 relative to the unix epoch 1970-01-01 00:00:00 +0000 (UTC). Since the timestamp is stored in a (64 bit signed) Nushell 
``int``
 type, this limits the range of dates that can be represented to approximately 21-sep-1677 through 11-apr-2262.
In prior versions, Nushell attempted to extend the range of representable dates by allowing multiple resolutions of timestamps (seconds, milliseconds as well as nanoseconds) to be stored and relied on arbitrary range check heuristics to disambiguate the value intended. However, there were bugs in the checks and incorrect results could be produced.
With this change 
``<int> | into datetime``
 assumes the input is a number of nanoseconds and can never produce a date outside this range:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
гЂ‰"7fffffffffffffff" | into int -r 16 | into datetime
Fri, 11 Apr 2262 23:47:16 +0000 (in 239 years)
гЂ‰("7fffffffffffffff" | into int -r 16) * -1 | into datetime
Tue, 21 Sep 1677 00:12:43 +0000 (345 years ago)

```
The timestamp epoch is the standard unix epoch. Note the timezone is UTC/GMT:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
гЂ‰0 | into datetime
Thu, 01 Jan 1970 00:00:00 +0000 (53 years ago)

```
``<datetime> | into int``
 can now produce an error if the input is outside the supported range:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
гЂ‰1492-10-12 | into int
Error: nu::shell::incorrect_value

  Г— Incorrect value.
   в•­в”Ђ[entry #51:1:1]
 1 в”‚ 1492-10-12 | into int
   В·              в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
   В·                  в•°в”Ђв”Ђ DateTime out of timestamp range 1677-09-21T00:12:43 and 2262-04-11T23:47:16
   в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
And finally, although not strictly required by the above fix, 
``<date> | date to-record``
 and 
``<date> | date to-table``
 now have a 
``nanosecond``
 field containing the subsecond residue of the input value (however it was produced).
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
гЂ‰"7fffffffffffffff" | into int -r 16 | into datetime | date to-record
в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
в”‚ year       в”‚ 2262      в”‚
в”‚ month      в”‚ 4         в”‚
в”‚ day        в”‚ 11        в”‚
в”‚ hour       в”‚ 23        в”‚
в”‚ minute     в”‚ 47        в”‚
в”‚ second     в”‚ 16        в”‚
в”‚ nanosecond в”‚ 854775807 в”‚
в”‚ timezone   в”‚ +00:00    в”‚
в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї
гЂ‰"7fffffffffffffff" | into int -r 16 | into datetime | date to-table
в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
в”‚ # в”‚ year в”‚ month в”‚ day в”‚ hour в”‚ minute в”‚ second в”‚ nanosecond в”‚ timezone в”‚
в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
в”‚ 0 в”‚ 2262 в”‚     4 в”‚  11 в”‚   23 в”‚     47 в”‚     16 в”‚  854775807 в”‚ +00:00   в”‚
в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
’Щ@ea363090318e7e62d3423008a72b1ffc25049d1bda2695e0bb80e5efa7876f10Ъ?Title: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: )
Content:
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/7947] New format for xml data created and accepted by 
``from xml``
 and 
``to xml``
 commands (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/7947] #7947
).
Commands 
``from xml``
 and 
``to xml``
 now use format where each xml entry is represented by a single 
``{tag: <tag name> attributes: <tag attributes> content: [<child entries>]}``
 record. Special xml entries also use this record, replacing irrelevant fields with 
``null``
 for easier use.
Reading some simple xml:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
гЂ‰'<release>
    <project repo="https://github.com/nushell/nushell">nushell</project>
    <version>0.77</version>
    <message>Now with better xml!</message>
  </release>' | from xml
в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
