Path: )
Content:
``$nu``
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8306] [link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8353] The builtin 
``$nu``
 variable now contains new entries:
``is-interactive``
: Nushell was launched in interactive mode
``is-login``
: Nushell was launched in login mode
``startup_time``
: Nushell's startup time
’Щ@164d54899c40c9ebadac46a7e05012e9e781e4f848f4a3c4ccd37d0121793766Ъ
Title: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: )
Content:
``http``
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8135] [link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8144] The 
``http``
 command now has more subcommands and existing subcommands have been reworked:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
> help http
Various commands for working with http methods.

You must use one of the following subcommands. Using this command as-is will only produce this help message.

Search terms: network, fetch, pull, request, download, curl, wget

Usage:
  > http

Subcommands:
  http delete - Delete the specified resource.
  http get - Fetch the contents from a URL.
  http head - Get the headers from a URL.
  http patch - Patch a body to a URL.
  http post - Post a body to a URL.
  http put - Put a body to a URL.

Flags:
  -h, --help - Display the help message for this command

Signatures:
  <nothing> | http -> <string>

```
Make sure to browse the help messages of these commands. They contain fully functional examples thanks to pointing at www.example.com.
’Щ@027465dc7b6a482b6b4a2ca1b3a857fb0f43112ac59abf51f6db1e4c2386923cЪҐTitle: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: )
Content:
``help``
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8189] When commands define expected results for their examples, the output is now shown just below the associated examples.
Let's take the 
``merge``
 command as an example!
Before the change, the output of 
``help merge``
 would give
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
Examples:
  Add an 'index' column to the input table
  > [a b c] | wrap name | merge ( [1 2 3] | wrap index )

  Merge two records
  > {a: 1, b: 2} | merge {c: 3}

  Merge two tables, overwriting overlapping columns
  > [{columnA: A0 columnB: B0}] | merge [{columnA: 'A0*'}]

```
Now, it gives the output of all the example commands:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
Examples:
  Add an 'index' column to the input table
  > [a b c] | wrap name | merge ( [1 2 3] | wrap index )
  в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
  в”‚ # в”‚ name в”‚
  в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
  в”‚ 1 в”‚ a    в”‚
  в”‚ 2 в”‚ b    в”‚
  в”‚ 3 в”‚ c    в”‚
  в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

  Merge two records
  > {a: 1, b: 2} | merge {c: 3}
  в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
  в”‚ a в”‚ 1 в”‚
  в”‚ b в”‚ 2 в”‚
  в”‚ c в”‚ 3 в”‚
  в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

  Merge two tables, overwriting overlapping columns
  > [{columnA: A0 columnB: B0}] | merge [{columnA: 'A0*'}]
  в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
  в”‚ # в”‚ columnA в”‚ columnB в”‚
  в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
  в”‚ 0 в”‚ A0*     в”‚ B0      в”‚
  в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
:bulb: 
Note

the website has been modified accordingly with the same outputs.
’Щ@2ab5040d1191e5c3da470086811a01a9cf05eb8a6d5d6903f46bf892947ebce0Ъ7Title: title: Nushell 0.77
Path: Breaking changes
Content:
Alias changes, see above
Comments on the same line as code now require a space before 
`` #``
 to be recognized as such. This allows you to have a string 
``foo#bar``
 with a pound sign. (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8151] #8151
)
``env``
 command has been removed, use 
``$env``
 instead (https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8185)
``str trim``
 no longer has 
``--all``
, 
``--both``
, and 
``--format``
 flags. 
``str replace``
 should be an adequate replacement; please let us know if it is not (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8205] #8205
)
The changes to timestamp handling noted above (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8244] #8244
) can require code changes to existing scripts:
Saved data containing the results of an old datetime-to-timestamp conversion will 
not
 deserialize correctly when read back by the current version of Nushell. In general, Nushell will produce incorrect datetime values without noting an error.
``<int> | into datetime``
 now assumes nanosecond scaling for all timestamps. You must ensure all timestamps computed by your script or retrieved from external sources are scaled appropriately.
``<date> | into int``
 can now fail, as noted above. You cannot rely on this operation to persist a arbitrary date.
The change to 
``from xml``
 and 
``to xml``
 commands noted above (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/7947] #7947
) will require to update scripts relying on old output/input format.
``mkdir``
, 
``cp``
, 
``mv``
 and 
``rm``
 return 
``nothing``
. Errors and actions with 
``--verbose``
 flag are printed to stderr instead (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8014] #8014
).
Plugin authors relying on 
``nu_protocol::Value``
 may need to update their code to account for a change to 
``Value::Error``
 (
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8375] #8375
)
Different types of lists can now be appended. This can break scripts that were relying on the stricter behavior (https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/8157)
